1
00:00:10,064 --> 00:00:11,760
This is a really nice room!

2
00:00:12,316 --> 00:00:14,270
Yeah, it sounds thick.
Too bad he's not coming.

3
00:00:14,474 --> 00:00:16,930
Look, I talked to him myself.
He'll be here.

4
00:00:17,135 --> 00:00:17,580
Right.

5
00:00:17,785 --> 00:00:21,286
You're the one who said the song could
use a horn part, so I got the best.

6
00:00:21,287 --> 00:00:21,992
John Henry!

7
00:00:21,993 --> 00:00:23,113
Do you think I'm stupid?

8
00:00:23,114 --> 00:00:25,150
Of course I do, but that's not the point.

9
00:00:26,177 --> 00:00:27,177
He'll be here, okay?

10
00:00:35,717 --> 00:00:36,717
Take a left up ahead.

11
00:00:37,307 --> 00:00:40,160
South Street?
I canceled this gig.

12
00:00:40,410 --> 00:00:43,010
You said you didn't want to
do any sessions for a while.

13
00:00:43,210 --> 00:00:44,210
For a while.

14
00:00:44,360 --> 00:00:45,920
I called her, I un-cancelled it.

15
00:00:46,900 --> 00:00:47,950
But you up to it?

16
00:00:48,160 --> 00:00:49,340
Let's find out.

17
00:00:53,160 --> 00:00:57,110
You lied to me, John Henry's
never gonna show up!

18
00:00:58,200 --> 00:00:59,200
Will you stop?

19
00:00:59,290 --> 00:01:00,739
It's been, like, two hours.

20
00:01:00,740 --> 00:01:02,040
And we will keep waiting.

21
00:01:02,240 --> 00:01:04,099
I mean, you've heard this
guy play and you know

22
00:01:04,100 --> 00:01:06,100
what he does, so can you
just shut up, Tommy?

23
00:01:09,120 --> 00:01:10,120
Oh, my God!

24
00:01:11,680 --> 00:01:12,680
Am I late?

25
00:01:22,300 --> 00:01:23,340
You need to hear it again?

26
00:01:24,460 --> 00:01:26,290
Nope, I get it. Let's try one.

27
00:01:26,490 --> 00:01:28,400
See what we get. Let's do it.

28
00:02:02,270 --> 00:02:05,539
John! You okay? You okay?

29
00:02:05,540 --> 00:02:07,280
I can't breathe, I can't breathe.

30
00:02:08,840 --> 00:02:10,160
Call an ambulance!

31
00:02:10,980 --> 00:02:11,980
Now!

32
00:03:00,180 --> 00:03:01,180
I want in.

33
00:03:03,430 --> 00:03:05,300
John Henry Giles, you a fan of his music?

34
00:03:05,500 --> 00:03:06,500
He's a musician?

35
00:03:08,180 --> 00:03:10,979
That paralysis thing, guy
can't walk for two years

36
00:03:10,980 --> 00:03:13,270
and nobody knows why, that
seems mildly interesting.

37
00:03:13,420 --> 00:03:15,149
Forget his paralysis.

38
00:03:15,150 --> 00:03:16,830
Tell that to the rest of his bowling team.

39
00:03:17,220 --> 00:03:18,999
As far as this hospital is concerned,

40
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:20,699
this is a simple case of low-bar pneumonia.

41
00:03:20,700 --> 00:03:21,360
Boring.

42
00:03:21,361 --> 00:03:22,519
But that “not walking” thing,

43
00:03:22,520 --> 00:03:24,220
that could turn into something serious!

44
00:03:24,780 --> 00:03:28,349
Marty Hamilton is his
primary physician out in California.

45
00:03:28,350 --> 00:03:29,439
He's dealing with the paralysis.

46
00:03:29,440 --> 00:03:30,290
Know all about it.

47
00:03:30,291 --> 00:03:32,399
Multiple treatments,
multiple surgeries.

48
00:03:32,400 --> 00:03:35,019
Making real progress.
Fixed everything but the legs.

49
00:03:35,020 --> 00:03:37,480
Dr. Hamilton already called
and asked for your team.

50
00:03:37,930 --> 00:03:40,700
And by team, I don't mean you.

51
00:03:41,300 --> 00:03:43,210
Like I always say, there's
no "I" in "team".

52
00:03:44,150 --> 00:03:45,910
There is a "me", though,
if you jumble it up.

53
00:03:47,220 --> 00:03:49,109
Foreman did his residency with Hamilton.

54
00:03:49,110 --> 00:03:52,580
I know. I did accidentally glance
at his resume before I hired him.

55
00:03:52,790 --> 00:03:54,479
He wants someone he can trust.

56
00:03:54,480 --> 00:03:56,259
He must have spoken to
Foreman's parole officer.

57
00:03:56,260 --> 00:03:59,149
Someone who will stick to the pneumonia.

58
00:03:59,150 --> 00:04:02,349
John Henry's on an experimental
protocol for the paralysis.

59
00:04:02,350 --> 00:04:04,230
I respect that.
I'm not going to get in his way.

60
00:04:04,750 --> 00:04:05,750
It's Foreman's case.

61
00:04:06,500 --> 00:04:08,020
It's pneumonia, he can handle it.

62
00:04:08,740 --> 00:04:11,280
Guy's already paralyzed,
how badly can he screw it up?

63
00:04:28,090 --> 00:04:29,920
So, what are his stats?

64
00:04:30,160 --> 00:04:32,159
Staying in the 90s on the nasal canula.

65
00:04:32,160 --> 00:04:33,130
Coughing up much sputa?

66
00:04:33,131 --> 00:04:35,059
Almost none, he seems to be stabilized.

67
00:04:35,060 --> 00:04:36,639
Dr. House, is there
anything back from Micro?

68
00:04:36,640 --> 00:04:38,870
Not yet. You gonna fire me?

69
00:04:39,070 --> 00:04:40,710
You can make up for it by washing my car.

70
00:04:41,180 --> 00:04:42,330
Oh, this is fun.

71
00:04:42,700 --> 00:04:44,850
Let's keep him on the
broad-spectrum antibiotics,

72
00:04:45,090 --> 00:04:47,279
and since he's displaying
septic physiology,

73
00:04:47,280 --> 00:04:49,090
draw blood for adrenal
and thyroid function.

74
00:04:52,180 --> 00:04:53,430
How about the paralysis?

75
00:04:53,800 --> 00:04:55,080
We're sticking to the pneumonia.

76
00:04:55,200 --> 00:04:56,809
Well, you certainly are, boss.

77
00:04:56,810 --> 00:04:59,069
Like a wet tongue sticks to dry ice.

78
00:04:59,070 --> 00:05:01,769
The paralysis has already been
diagnosed by Dr. Hamilton.

79
00:05:01,770 --> 00:05:02,640
It's ALS.

80
00:05:02,641 --> 00:05:05,160
Lou Gehrig's disease.
It's a lovely diagnosis.

81
00:05:05,400 --> 00:05:06,440
They make movies about it.

82
00:05:06,680 --> 00:05:09,869
No tests, no treatment.
It's a disease of exclusion.

83
00:05:09,870 --> 00:05:11,670
Because Hamilton has
excluded everything else.

84
00:05:11,910 --> 00:05:12,910
I haven't.

85
00:05:17,790 --> 00:05:18,790
What else could it be?

86
00:05:19,710 --> 00:05:21,620
Guillain-Barre, which would be reversible.

87
00:05:21,860 --> 00:05:22,360
Excellent.

88
00:05:22,620 --> 00:05:25,840
No, the progression of the
paralysis would be symmetric.

89
00:05:26,040 --> 00:05:26,650
This wasn't.

90
00:05:26,890 --> 00:05:27,959
Transverse myelitis.

91
00:05:27,960 --> 00:05:29,359
Hamilton tested for it.
Negative.

92
00:05:29,360 --> 00:05:31,419
And he was negative for
masses, and AVM, and...

93
00:05:31,420 --> 00:05:32,989
Antibodies could be attacking the nerve.

94
00:05:32,990 --> 00:05:34,479
Multifocal motoneuropathy.

95
00:05:34,480 --> 00:05:37,000
Uncommon, but it fits.
It's also treatable.

96
00:05:37,440 --> 00:05:39,340
Did Hamilton try putting the guy on IVIG?

97
00:05:39,580 --> 00:05:40,769
No, because the MRI showed...

98
00:05:40,770 --> 00:05:42,230
Well, let's do an MRI of our own.

99
00:05:46,850 --> 00:05:48,880
Guys? It's my case.

100
00:05:50,520 --> 00:05:52,710
ALS fits. It even predicts the pneumonia.

101
00:05:53,180 --> 00:05:54,480
The paralysis is progressive.

102
00:05:55,360 --> 00:05:56,460
It's a death sentence.

103
00:05:57,580 --> 00:05:58,920
That doesn't make it wrong.

104
00:06:17,890 --> 00:06:20,380
So, you think the breathing
stuff is connected to my ALS?

105
00:06:21,240 --> 00:06:22,240
It makes sense.

106
00:06:24,990 --> 00:06:26,660
So, it's just gonna get worse, huh?

107
00:06:26,710 --> 00:06:27,920
Well, Dr. Hamilton...

108
00:06:28,210 --> 00:06:30,100
Great guy. Really smart doctor,

109
00:06:30,540 --> 00:06:32,560
but his treatment obviously isn't working.

110
00:06:34,860 --> 00:06:35,899
Do you think I'm gonna die here,

111
00:06:35,900 --> 00:06:37,900
or you think I'm gonna
get to go back home first?

112
00:06:38,680 --> 00:06:40,609
An MRI would give us a better idea...

113
00:06:40,610 --> 00:06:42,959
An MRI? Come on. For pneumonia?

114
00:06:42,960 --> 00:06:44,159
Well, Dr. House thinks
we should test for...

115
00:06:44,160 --> 00:06:48,390
House? Yeah, I heard about him.
Obsessive son-of-a-bitch?

116
00:06:48,940 --> 00:06:49,940
That's him.

117
00:06:51,960 --> 00:06:53,880
So, who do you think is right?
Hamilton or House?

118
00:06:55,360 --> 00:06:57,400
They're both excellent physicians.

119
00:06:57,650 --> 00:06:58,650
Come on.

120
00:06:59,240 --> 00:07:02,690
One of 'em says ALS, the
other one says not ALS.

121
00:07:03,520 --> 00:07:04,890
You gotta pick one, son.

122
00:07:06,960 --> 00:07:08,360
Everything points to ALS.

123
00:07:09,980 --> 00:07:10,980
Then no MRI.

124
00:07:15,930 --> 00:07:18,279
And I want one of them
papers that say I, I

125
00:07:18,280 --> 00:07:20,060
don't want nothin' done
if something go bad.

126
00:07:20,590 --> 00:07:21,590
A DNR?

127
00:07:22,670 --> 00:07:24,419
Mr. Giles, you don't want to rush things...

128
00:07:24,420 --> 00:07:25,940
It's been two years, I ain't rushing.

129
00:07:26,640 --> 00:07:27,700
I wanna sign one.

130
00:07:30,350 --> 00:07:34,570
Now, while my arm still works.

131
00:08:00,460 --> 00:08:01,560
He signed a DNR.

132
00:08:05,150 --> 00:08:06,640
He rhymes with dinner?

133
00:08:07,960 --> 00:08:09,310
He signed a DNR.

134
00:08:10,040 --> 00:08:12,400
Oh. That makes more sense.

135
00:08:13,940 --> 00:08:15,360
You tell him it might not be ALS?

136
00:08:16,120 --> 00:08:17,120
No.

137
00:08:17,960 --> 00:08:20,010
Well, no wonder he signed.
Who wouldn't?

138
00:08:20,320 --> 00:08:22,900
I started him on IV
steroids and ancinthroid.

139
00:08:23,150 --> 00:08:24,150
Great.

140
00:08:24,660 --> 00:08:27,730
If it was my case, I'd be adding
a little IVIG to the mix.

141
00:08:28,060 --> 00:08:29,060
For his pneumonia?

142
00:08:29,630 --> 00:08:31,280
That's my story and I'm sticking to it.

143
00:08:32,940 --> 00:08:35,200
He doesn't want anything done.
No treatment.

144
00:08:36,120 --> 00:08:39,520
DNR means "do not resuscitate",
not "do not treat".

145
00:08:40,930 --> 00:08:43,250
You do nothing, it doesn't
matter which one of us is right.

146
00:08:46,780 --> 00:08:48,320
And hang on to that DNR.

147
00:08:48,730 --> 00:08:51,040
That signature could be worth
a lot of money real soon.

148
00:08:58,650 --> 00:09:00,490
This is Dr. Foreman.
What's Mr. Giles's status?

149
00:09:02,040 --> 00:09:04,710
Okay, increase the steroids
to 100mg every 12 hours,

150
00:09:04,910 --> 00:09:07,850
and, ah, start him on IVIG.

151
00:09:08,620 --> 00:09:11,150
Yeah, I'm sure. One gram per kilo.

152
00:09:13,370 --> 00:09:14,830
My nature isn't what it used to be.

153
00:09:15,370 --> 00:09:17,780
The little man has lost
some bounce in his step.

154
00:09:18,190 --> 00:09:20,840
He needs to crank it up,
have himself some fun this weekend.

155
00:09:22,120 --> 00:09:23,450
He wants the blue pills.

156
00:09:24,230 --> 00:09:26,450
You're talking about your
penis in the third person.

157
00:09:26,730 --> 00:09:28,670
Me and him, two people.

158
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:30,000
Separate vacations?

159
00:09:30,550 --> 00:09:31,940
That'd be a drag for one of you.

160
00:09:32,390 --> 00:09:33,710
I don't think you need the pills.

161
00:09:33,980 --> 00:09:35,790
I think you have a conflict of medications.

162
00:09:36,440 --> 00:09:39,340
You need to up your insulin to
"chocolate chip ice cream" levels.

163
00:09:40,140 --> 00:09:40,630
Insulin?

164
00:09:40,980 --> 00:09:41,980
Yeah, you remember.

165
00:09:42,250 --> 00:09:43,759
That's the stuff you take for the diabetes

166
00:09:43,760 --> 00:09:45,460
that you forgot to tell the nurse about.

167
00:09:46,510 --> 00:09:47,510
Your hands.

168
00:09:48,760 --> 00:09:51,330
No hair, which means nerve damage.

169
00:09:51,630 --> 00:09:53,969
And your shoes look about
two sizes too small

170
00:09:53,970 --> 00:09:56,180
which means you've lost
sensation in your feet.

171
00:09:56,770 --> 00:09:58,120
And then there's your pants.

172
00:09:58,520 --> 00:10:00,260
My pants tell you I have diabetes?

173
00:10:00,420 --> 00:10:01,790
No, they tell me you're an idiot.

174
00:10:02,470 --> 00:10:04,210
Powdered sugar on the right pant leg.

175
00:10:05,560 --> 00:10:07,450
Based on the two napkins
in your right pocket,

176
00:10:07,770 --> 00:10:10,040
I'm willing to bet it's not
your first donut of the day.

177
00:10:18,920 --> 00:10:20,000
You're giving me the pills?

178
00:10:20,670 --> 00:10:21,670
Sure, why not?

179
00:10:22,520 --> 00:10:25,360
If you've got heart disease from
ignoring the diabetes they'll kill you.

180
00:10:26,720 --> 00:10:29,220
Otherwise, you two have a fun weekend.

181
00:10:38,760 --> 00:10:39,790
O2 stats are dropping.

182
00:10:40,030 --> 00:10:40,660
Breath sounds?

183
00:10:40,910 --> 00:10:41,450
Junky.

184
00:10:41,450 --> 00:10:42,150
Mucus plug?

185
00:10:42,151 --> 00:10:44,580
No, it's our mistake.
He's sludging from the IVIG.

186
00:10:44,870 --> 00:10:46,079
Blood can't get through to his lungs.

187
00:10:46,080 --> 00:10:47,789
Start Heparin. 500ccs, IV push.

188
00:10:47,790 --> 00:10:50,730
He won't last long enough for it to work.
We've got to intubate him, stat.

189
00:10:51,770 --> 00:10:52,770
We can't!

190
00:10:53,380 --> 00:10:54,100
He's DNR.

191
00:10:54,100 --> 00:10:55,100
What?

192
00:11:03,720 --> 00:11:04,720
Someone likes music.

193
00:11:05,280 --> 00:11:06,280
Oh, yeah.

194
00:11:13,240 --> 00:11:15,089
His stats are in the 70s.
How long has he been like this?

195
00:11:15,090 --> 00:11:15,950
10 minutes.

196
00:11:15,951 --> 00:11:17,239
- Well, why aren't you doing?
- The IVIG put him

197
00:11:17,240 --> 00:11:18,319
into respiratory failure.

198
00:11:18,320 --> 00:11:19,479
You put him on the IVIG?

199
00:11:19,480 --> 00:11:20,480
We did this.

200
00:11:20,890 --> 00:11:22,370
So undo it! Chase!

201
00:11:22,860 --> 00:11:24,090
It's too late! We killed him.

202
00:11:24,290 --> 00:11:25,820
Nobody killed him!
He's not dead!

203
00:11:26,140 --> 00:11:27,140
Chase, intubate him!

204
00:11:27,880 --> 00:11:28,880
He's DNR.

205
00:11:40,110 --> 00:11:41,150
What are you doing?

206
00:11:46,920 --> 00:11:48,090
You can't do this!

207
00:11:50,580 --> 00:11:51,230
Bag.

208
00:11:51,590 --> 00:11:53,079
You can't do this!

209
00:11:53,080 --> 00:11:54,080
Bag!

210
00:12:02,630 --> 00:12:04,690
He had a bad reaction to
some medicine we gave him.

211
00:12:06,290 --> 00:12:07,360
What did you just do?

212
00:12:09,360 --> 00:12:10,460
He saved his life.

213
00:12:26,150 --> 00:12:28,700
He's stable on the ventilator.
Oxygenating well.

214
00:12:28,950 --> 00:12:30,699
The IVIG made him worse,

215
00:12:30,700 --> 00:12:34,070
which means multifocal
motoneuropathy was a bad diagnosis.

216
00:12:34,530 --> 00:12:35,699
Okay, what's really wrong with him?

217
00:12:35,700 --> 00:12:37,190
What's wrong with you?

218
00:12:37,390 --> 00:12:38,499
Everyone knows what's wrong with me.

219
00:12:38,500 --> 00:12:40,139
What's wrong with him
is much more interesting.

220
00:12:40,140 --> 00:12:42,200
You tubed him and he didn't wanna be tubed!

221
00:12:42,510 --> 00:12:44,509
He has a legal paper saying just that.

222
00:12:44,510 --> 00:12:47,490
To intubate or not to intubate,
that is the big ethical question.

223
00:12:47,900 --> 00:12:50,519
Actually, I was hoping we could avoid it,
maybe just practice some medicine.

224
00:12:50,520 --> 00:12:51,670
There's no question.

225
00:12:52,050 --> 00:12:53,579
It's the patient's decision...

226
00:12:53,580 --> 00:12:55,479
if the patient is competent to make it,

227
00:12:55,480 --> 00:12:57,849
if his thyroid numbers
aren't making him sad.

228
00:12:57,850 --> 00:12:59,319
Oh, my God.
You don't believe that.

229
00:12:59,320 --> 00:13:00,619
His thyroid levels were a little...

230
00:13:00,620 --> 00:13:03,219
It's nothing. Do not defend him.

231
00:13:03,220 --> 00:13:04,610
Why did he sign that DNR?

232
00:13:05,130 --> 00:13:06,130
I didn't talk him into...

233
00:13:06,131 --> 00:13:10,299
No, he signed the DNR 'cause he didn't
want a slow and painful death from ALS.

234
00:13:10,300 --> 00:13:12,259
What was happening to him had
nothing to do with his ALS.

235
00:13:12,260 --> 00:13:14,960
Right! Exactly! It's the
IVIG, you screwed up!

236
00:13:15,670 --> 00:13:17,860
You're not gonna let him die
because you screwed up!

237
00:13:19,300 --> 00:13:21,990
Technically, your case.
You screwed up.

238
00:13:22,780 --> 00:13:23,849
Is that what this is about?

239
00:13:23,850 --> 00:13:25,729
Looking bad in front of your old boss?

240
00:13:25,730 --> 00:13:26,969
You assaulted that man.

241
00:13:26,970 --> 00:13:28,539
Fine. I'll never do it again.

242
00:13:28,540 --> 00:13:29,140
Yes, you will.

243
00:13:29,350 --> 00:13:31,110
All the more reason this
debate is pointless.

244
00:13:37,120 --> 00:13:39,920
His lungs are worse. Any theories?

245
00:13:41,420 --> 00:13:43,699
Oh, I'm sure he just went
to the little boys' room.

246
00:13:43,700 --> 00:13:44,600
Come on, people.

247
00:13:44,601 --> 00:13:46,360
Uh, vasculitis?

248
00:13:46,610 --> 00:13:48,039
Wouldn't likely hit both lungs.

249
00:13:48,040 --> 00:13:49,920
It could be Wegener's granulomatosis.

250
00:13:50,920 --> 00:13:51,920
Dr. House?

251
00:13:54,780 --> 00:13:56,819
Cuddy sent me a stripper again?

252
00:13:56,820 --> 00:13:59,060
Ah, love that woman.
So thoughtful.

253
00:14:00,160 --> 00:14:01,160
Sorry.

254
00:14:02,440 --> 00:14:05,319
There are case reports of Wegener's
hitting both the lungs and the spine.

255
00:14:05,320 --> 00:14:07,160
Well, it's not great, but
it's better than ALS.

256
00:14:07,390 --> 00:14:08,460
At least it's treatable.

257
00:14:08,710 --> 00:14:09,710
It's a restraining order.

258
00:14:09,850 --> 00:14:12,279
You're not to come within 50
feet of John Henry Giles,

259
00:14:12,280 --> 00:14:15,260
and they've asked the DA to file
criminal charges for battery.

260
