00:29:18,690 --> 00:29:19,690
Kinda sorta.

509
00:29:19,940 --> 00:29:20,940
Serious?

510
00:29:22,220 --> 00:29:23,220
I don't know. Could be.

511
00:29:23,640 --> 00:29:25,130
You think she would enjoy L.A.?

512
00:29:43,880 --> 00:29:45,260
Hamilton offered me a job.

513
00:29:46,460 --> 00:29:47,160
You gonna take it?

514
00:29:47,161 --> 00:29:48,379
I haven't decided.

515
00:29:48,380 --> 00:29:50,269
You already have the most
prestigious fellowship.

516
00:29:50,270 --> 00:29:51,290
It's a partnership.

517
00:29:51,870 --> 00:29:55,700
Three times the money, car allowance,
moving expense, pension plan,

518
00:29:55,940 --> 00:29:58,659
the chance to work for a guy who gives
a crap what other people think.

519
00:29:58,660 --> 00:30:00,460
So, why didn't you just tell him yes?

520
00:30:01,160 --> 00:30:02,370
I made a commitment here.

521
00:30:03,450 --> 00:30:04,070
Right.

522
00:30:04,270 --> 00:30:05,976
House would let you out
of it in a heartbeat.

523
00:30:06,000 --> 00:30:08,190
Or he wouldn't, just to jerk me around.

524
00:30:08,910 --> 00:30:10,270
Would you guys have taken the job?

525
00:30:10,590 --> 00:30:11,450
Don't need the money.

526
00:30:11,451 --> 00:30:13,360
I'm not like you.
I don't hate House.

527
00:30:14,450 --> 00:30:16,970
You guys really don't have a problem
with him, with what he did?

528
00:30:17,430 --> 00:30:19,249
He knows we disagree with his choice.

529
00:30:19,250 --> 00:30:19,980
Choice?

530
00:30:20,250 --> 00:30:22,510
Chase, it's not apples and
oranges, its right and wrong.

531
00:30:22,840 --> 00:30:24,280
And he does it like he doesn't care!

532
00:30:24,630 --> 00:30:26,579
He assaults the guy and
moves on to the next

533
00:30:26,580 --> 00:30:27,589
differential diagnosis
like it's nothing...

534
00:30:27,590 --> 00:30:28,660
What do you want from him?

535
00:30:28,790 --> 00:30:30,519
More hand-wringing, more torment?

536
00:30:30,520 --> 00:30:31,979
You want him to
cry himself to sleep at night?

537
00:30:31,980 --> 00:30:35,479
Yeah! Yeah, I want some clue
that he knows it's a big deal.

538
00:30:35,480 --> 00:30:37,739
That it scares him, that it matters.

539
00:30:37,740 --> 00:30:40,150
Whoa, what's that?

540
00:30:42,270 --> 00:30:43,290
It was a stroke!

541
00:30:44,930 --> 00:30:45,930
Well done, Cameron.

542
00:30:46,280 --> 00:30:48,680
House called it.
The arm and legs are unrelated.

543
00:30:49,840 --> 00:30:52,040
You make enough calls,
one of them is bound to be right.

544
00:30:52,200 --> 00:30:55,339
Yeah, he's
just a lucky, lucky guy.

545
00:30:55,340 --> 00:30:59,580
Listen, listen, I just think it wouldn't
hurt him to learn a little humility.

546
00:31:00,880 --> 00:31:02,100
So, what's the verdict?

547
00:31:03,560 --> 00:31:06,300
Embolus.
The arm problem's caused by a clot.

548
00:31:06,670 --> 00:31:09,060
There's a good chance we can
still bust the clot with TPA.

549
00:31:09,980 --> 00:31:12,130
Do it. See
what happens to his arm.

550
00:31:22,570 --> 00:31:24,310
We found a blood clot in your brain.

551
00:31:25,010 --> 00:31:27,360
We'd like to start you on heparin,
it's a blood thinner.

552
00:31:28,580 --> 00:31:29,690
What are the side effects?

553
00:31:30,460 --> 00:31:32,870
Well, your lungs are kind of
chewed up from the pneumonia.

554
00:31:33,320 --> 00:31:34,760
Good chance there'll be an infusion.

555
00:31:34,980 --> 00:31:35,980
Bleeding?

556
00:31:36,300 --> 00:31:37,529
Into his lungs.

557
00:31:37,530 --> 00:31:40,020
It's our best chance to give
you back the use of your arm.

558
00:31:40,220 --> 00:31:42,050
I don't need my arm without my air.

559
00:31:42,330 --> 00:31:43,730
The damage would likely be minimal.

560
00:31:44,230 --> 00:31:45,230
No.

561
00:31:47,930 --> 00:31:48,930
It's his call.

562
00:31:51,560 --> 00:31:53,240
Or we could do an embolectomy.

563
00:31:53,700 --> 00:31:56,070
Basically, we'd go in
and pull the clot out.

564
00:31:56,690 --> 00:31:59,600
He's saying no to drugs and you're
recommending brain surgery?

565
00:32:00,140 --> 00:32:01,950
Bypasses risk to the lungs.

566
00:32:02,230 --> 00:32:03,379
It'll either help your arm, or...

567
00:32:03,380 --> 00:32:04,380
Or it'll kill me.

568
00:32:04,870 --> 00:32:07,150
From your point of view,
it's a win-win.

569
00:32:09,420 --> 00:32:10,420
Okay.

570
00:32:11,340 --> 00:32:12,820
We'll set up the procedure for today.

571
00:32:25,090 --> 00:32:26,650
We're in your carotid artery.

572
00:32:27,630 --> 00:32:29,990
This is going to take us all
the way up into your brain.

573
00:32:31,560 --> 00:32:32,560
You all right?

574
00:32:33,800 --> 00:32:34,800
Yes.

575
00:32:42,210 --> 00:32:43,819
The sludge is blocking the blood

576
00:32:43,820 --> 00:32:45,900
flow to the part of
the brain that controls your arm.

577
00:32:55,740 --> 00:32:56,740
All done.

578
00:32:57,480 --> 00:32:58,650
You still okay?

579
00:33:00,840 --> 00:33:02,000
I think so.

580
00:33:03,140 --> 00:33:04,140
I don't know, I guess...

581
00:33:04,970 --> 00:33:08,150
It's just with Dr. Hamilton here,
I notice a difference in styles.

582
00:33:09,640 --> 00:33:12,010
His style involves humility.

583
00:33:13,410 --> 00:33:17,240
Another difference in our styles:
I don't care much for apologies.

584
00:33:17,900 --> 00:33:18,690
You can go.

585
00:33:18,691 --> 00:33:21,209
I didn't know you were standing
there when I said that, okay?

586
00:33:21,210 --> 00:33:22,240
It was completely rude.

587
00:33:22,520 --> 00:33:24,339
Do you mean genuine humility?

588
00:33:24,340 --> 00:33:26,969
You know, with all the self-doubt
and the self-questioning,

589
00:33:26,970 --> 00:33:30,889
or Hamilton's polite, patronizing
"Aw, shucks" humility?

590
00:33:30,890 --> 00:33:32,239
You're both excellent doctors.

591
00:33:32,240 --> 00:33:33,120
Thank you.

592
00:33:33,121 --> 00:33:37,190
And humility is an important quality.
Especially if you're wrong a lot.

593
00:33:37,480 --> 00:33:39,190
You've been wrong every step of the way.

594
00:33:44,710 --> 00:33:49,430
Of course, when you're right, self-doubt
doesn't help anybody, does it?

595
00:33:56,160 --> 00:33:57,160
We gotta go.

596
00:34:05,090 --> 00:34:06,120
Congratulations, Gregg.

597
00:34:08,150 --> 00:34:09,360
Congratulations...

598
00:34:09,560 --> 00:34:10,560
Why, Marty?

599
00:34:10,670 --> 00:34:12,860
John woke up, he can use his arm.

600
00:34:14,180 --> 00:34:15,180
Thank you.

601
00:34:15,330 --> 00:34:17,090
Now look, I know we've had our differences,

602
00:34:17,290 --> 00:34:20,440
but I think when a person does something
well it ought to be recognized.

603
00:34:21,440 --> 00:34:22,440
The phone works.

604
00:34:23,060 --> 00:34:26,240
Next time you want to make me feel
all warm and fuzzy, leave a message.

605
00:34:26,730 --> 00:34:29,100
Don't get me wrong,
I'm overcome with joy.

606
00:34:29,540 --> 00:34:30,140
Doc?

607
00:34:30,530 --> 00:34:30,870
Yeah?

608
00:34:30,870 --> 00:34:31,870
What?

609
00:34:32,640 --> 00:34:33,930
You just touched my leg.

610
00:34:35,080 --> 00:34:36,880
What, you gonna charge
me with assault again?

611
00:34:37,720 --> 00:34:41,060
No, I felt it.

612
00:34:51,640 --> 00:34:53,710
He now has feeling all the way up to calf.

613
00:34:53,910 --> 00:34:56,000
This is the way medicine evolved.

614
00:34:57,010 --> 00:34:58,630
Patients sometimes get better.

615
00:34:58,870 --> 00:35:01,800
You have no idea why, but unless you
give a reason they won't pay you.

616
00:35:02,420 --> 00:35:04,020
Anybody notice if there's a full moon?

617
00:35:04,440 --> 00:35:06,449
You're saying he just
spontaneously got better?

618
00:35:06,450 --> 00:35:09,070
No, I'm saying let's rule out the
lunar god and go from there.

619
00:35:09,270 --> 00:35:10,670
Something he's on is working.

620
00:35:11,400 --> 00:35:14,260
The enzyme replacement protocol
is working, reversing the ALS.

621
00:35:14,500 --> 00:35:16,279
The timing doesn't suspicious to you?

622
00:35:16,280 --> 00:35:18,200
Do you think Dr.
House will see it that way?

623
00:35:18,600 --> 00:35:20,240
Figure it's his medication doing the job?

624
00:35:20,650 --> 00:35:21,670
I'm sure he will.

625
00:35:21,990 --> 00:35:23,140
It's one of ours.

626
00:35:23,470 --> 00:35:25,470
How do we figure out which
drug is doing the trick?

627
00:35:25,630 --> 00:35:27,680
Easy. We stop all of them.

628
00:35:27,920 --> 00:35:29,269
One of those drugs is helping him.

629
00:35:29,270 --> 00:35:30,270
And the rest?

630
00:35:30,740 --> 00:35:33,219
Steroids, antibiotics,
anti-inflammatories,

631
00:35:33,220 --> 00:35:34,826
they're toxic if we leave
him on all of them.

632
00:35:34,850 --> 00:35:35,740
He'll walk again.

633
00:35:35,741 --> 00:35:37,019
Yeah, to his own funeral.

634
00:35:37,020 --> 00:35:38,759
But if we stop
everything, he'll get worse.

635
00:35:38,760 --> 00:35:41,409
True. And then we'll add our
medications back, one at a time.

636
00:35:41,410 --> 00:35:43,210
If he gets better, then
we'll have our answer.

637
00:35:43,260 --> 00:35:44,420
And if he doesn't get better?

638
00:35:45,070 --> 00:35:46,070
Then we're in trouble.

639
00:35:46,870 --> 00:35:48,270
Not as much as he is.

640
00:35:49,460 --> 00:35:50,660
I suppose that was your point.

641
00:35:54,050 --> 00:35:57,490
I assume you want me to convince
Hamilton to stop his treatments, too?

642
00:35:57,880 --> 00:35:58,650
Don't care.

643
00:35:58,651 --> 00:36:01,569
You know at least five of the
medications are part of his protocol?

644
00:36:01,570 --> 00:36:04,250
If his stuff was helping the guy would
be playing tennis months ago.

645
00:36:04,610 --> 00:36:06,330
It's our round of treatment that's helping.

646
00:36:06,720 --> 00:36:08,870
Right. So that's what you'll stop.

647
00:36:12,450 --> 00:36:13,789
So your philosophy is,

648
00:36:13,790 --> 00:36:16,196
"If they don't want treatment,
they get it shoved down their throat,

649
00:36:16,220 --> 00:36:18,780
but if it might cure their paralysis,
whoa, better slow down."

650
00:36:19,410 --> 00:36:20,410
Yeah.

651
00:36:20,610 --> 00:36:23,130
My old philosophy used to
be "Live and let live,"

652
00:36:23,830 --> 00:36:27,470
but I'm taking this needlepoint class and
they gave us these really big pillows.

653
00:36:28,020 --> 00:36:29,979
What's your philosophy
on employee relations?

654
00:36:29,980 --> 00:36:31,250
That's a very tiny pillow.

655
00:36:31,990 --> 00:36:34,210
Great. Sounds like you
know what you're doing.

656
00:36:35,530 --> 00:36:37,470
Gregg. Can I have a word?

657
00:36:37,780 --> 00:36:39,880
Can it wait for the commercial, Marty?

658
00:36:40,770 --> 00:36:42,110
Say "hi" to my friend, Jimmy.

659
00:36:44,080 --> 00:36:45,080
Pleasure.

660
00:36:45,970 --> 00:36:48,120
Your diagnostic trial...

661
00:36:48,320 --> 00:36:50,420
Seriously, commercial's
in about five minutes.

662
00:36:50,660 --> 00:36:51,669
It's a dangerous game.

663
00:36:51,670 --> 00:36:53,260
Only if we're watching in the bathtub.

664
00:36:54,260 --> 00:36:57,149
I need to know exactly what
medications you were giving John Henry.

665
00:36:57,150 --> 00:36:58,150
Forget it.

666
00:36:58,220 --> 00:37:00,879
And if Foreman tells you what
John Henry used to be on...

667
00:37:00,880 --> 00:37:01,880
You're gonna fire him?

668
00:37:02,770 --> 00:37:06,309
Nope. Make him live out every
day of his two-year contract.

669
00:37:06,310 --> 00:37:07,459
Foreman asked to leave?

670
00:37:07,460 --> 00:37:08,240
Not yet.

671
00:37:08,241 --> 00:37:09,289
But how do you know I made him an...

672
00:37:09,290 --> 00:37:11,790
You're a polite twit,
but you're not an idiot.

673
00:37:12,740 --> 00:37:15,420
I need to know what medications
you've taken him off of.

674
00:37:18,870 --> 00:37:21,160
Wait a second.
You're not an idiot.

675
00:37:24,970 --> 00:37:29,170
You need to know what medications
I've stopped, because...

676
00:37:32,170 --> 00:37:33,170
He's getting worse.

677
00:37:39,030 --> 00:37:40,630
Right now you still work for me.
Come on!

678
00:37:43,870 --> 00:37:45,500
No feeling, no wiggling.

679
00:37:45,750 --> 00:37:47,790
The bad news is, John Henry's
back where he started.

680
00:37:47,940 --> 00:37:49,520
The good news is, Hamilton looks bad.

681
00:37:49,900 --> 00:37:52,586
Yeah, it's not whether you win or lose,
it's whether the other guy loses.

682
00:37:52,610 --> 00:37:53,909
What was the first thing we put him on?

683
00:37:53,910 --> 00:37:55,369
Steroids, for the pneumonia.

684
00:37:55,370 --> 00:37:58,049
Well, put him back on them.
Give them 24 hours, see what happens.

685
00:37:58,050 --> 00:37:59,300
His lungs aren't great.

686
00:37:59,650 --> 00:38:01,239
It might cause another
respiratory collapse.

687
00:38:01,240 --> 00:38:01,800
Sure hope not.

688
00:38:02,040 --> 00:38:04,279
I didn't much like that lawyer.
And get an MRI.

689
00:38:04,280 --> 00:38:05,699
He already got one. And an MRA.

690
00:38:05,700 --> 00:38:07,900
Well, obviously something is different now.
Do it again.

691
00:38:08,210 --> 00:38:10,690
Chase, take care of the scan.
Cameron, put him on the steroids.

692
00:38:14,570 --> 00:38:15,870
We should probably talk, huh?

693
00:38:22,120 --> 00:38:23,120
Thin cuts.

694
00:38:23,620 --> 00:38:24,260
What levels?

695
00:38:24,640 --> 00:38:27,410
T9 through the quarter-equinus,
same as the last time.

696
00:38:29,270 --> 00:38:31,670
You really think House would let
Foreman out of his contract?

697
00:38:31,980 --> 00:38:32,670
He has to.

698
00:38:32,870 --> 00:38:34,790
If he doesn't, he's telling
Foreman he needs him.

699
00:38:35,430 --> 00:38:36,500
House can't handle that.

700
00:38:42,850 --> 00:38:43,850
Oh, my God!

701
00:38:49,780 --> 00:38:50,810
I checked him out.

702
00:38:52,870 --> 00:38:54,280
He's a great doctor.

703
00:38:56,150 --> 00:38:57,460
You think he's better than I am.

704
00:38:58,610 --> 00:38:59,680
This about your ego?

705
00:39:00,790 --> 00:39:01,900
Answer the question.

706
00:39:04,020 --> 00:39:06,020
It's not going to change
how I think about myself.

707
00:39:06,560 --> 00:39:08,060
Might affect my opinion of you,

708
00:39:08,460 --> 00:39:10,540
but that
shouldn't affect your opinion of yourself.

709
00:39:12,150 --> 00:39:13,300
Now I'm getting confused.

710
00:39:13,640 --> 00:39:16,560
If you think he's a better doctor than
I am, then you should take the job.

711
00:39:17,120 --> 00:39:19,139
Otherwise, you should get
him to buy you two or

712
00:39:19,140 --> 00:39:22,759
three more nostalgic lunches
and politely decline.

713
00:39:22,760 --> 00:39:23,590
It's that simple?

714
00:39:23,591 --> 00:39:26,089
I should just ignore the mockery and abuse?

715
00:39:26,090 --> 00:39:27,719
Oh, how do I abuse you?

716
00:39:27,720 --> 00:39:29,989
How do you not?
If I make a mistake...

717
00:39:29,990 --> 00:39:31,919
I hold you accountable, so what?

718
00:39:31,920 --> 00:39:35,219
Dr. Hamilton forgives.
He's capable of moving on.

719
00:39:35,220 --> 00:39:36,639
That is not what he does!

720
00:39:36,640 --> 00:39:38,069
I screwed up his case, he told me...

721
00:39:38,070 --> 00:39:41,809
He never said you were forgiven.
I was there, he said it wasn't your fault.

722
00:39:41,810 --> 00:39:42,200
So?

723
00:39:42,201 --> 00:39:43,710
So, it was.

724
00:39:44,850 --> 00:39:46,859
You took a chance,
you did something great.

725
00:39:46,860 --> 00:39:49,009
You were wrong,
but it was still great.

726
00:39:49,010 --> 00:39:50,610
You should feel great that it was great.

727
00:39:50,720 --> 00:39:52,440
You should feel
like crap that it was wrong.

728
00:39:52,840 --> 00:39:54,480
That's the difference between him and me.

729
00:39:54,680 --> 00:39:57,020
He thinks you do your job,
and what will be, will be.

730
00:39:57,220 --> 00:39:59,280
I think that what I do
and what you do matters.

731
00:40:01,580 --> 00:40:04,150
He sleeps better at night.
He shouldn't.

732
00:40:07,370 --> 00:40:08,879
Arteriovenous malformation.

733
00:40:08,880 --> 00:40:10,850
Intradural, compressing his spine.

734
00:40:13,220 --> 00:40:14,590
Causing his paralysis.

735
00:40:15,520 --> 00:40:17,580
How could Hamilton have missed an AVM?

736
00:40:17,970 --> 00:40:21,600
Well, we missed it, too.
'Cause it wasn't there before.

737
00:40:22,510 --> 00:40:24,080
You saying it just grew overnight?

738
00:40:24,750 --> 00:40:29,310
No. It was on the spine,
it wasn't on the MRI.

739
00:40:30,380 --> 00:40:32,120
Same anatomic location.

740
00:40:33,000 --> 00:40:34,000
It's not there.

741
00:40:34,790 --> 00:40:35,790
Well, what is there?

742
00:40:35,970 --> 00:40:36,970
Nothing.

743
00:40:37,900 --> 00:40:40,580
Or something that looks like nothing.

744
00:40:42,440 --> 00:40:43,729
Background noise, static.

745
00:40:43,730 --> 00:40:45,620
Scar tissue? Inflammation?

746
00:40:45,860 --> 00:40:48,260
If it's inflammation, the steroids
would have shrunk it down.

747
00:40:49,820 --> 00:40:51,120
Revealing the AVM,

748
00:40:52,090 --> 00:40:54,219
which has always been
there, hiding behind its

749
00:40:54,220 --> 00:40:56,170
own swelling. We remove
that, he'll walk again.

750
00:41:45,920 --> 00:41:46,920
Dr. House!

751
00:41:49,400 --> 00:41:51,280
Cora's meeting me outside with a limo.

752
00:41:52,690 --> 00:41:53,910
I'm being discharged.

753
00:41:55,420 --> 00:41:57,250
Fifty bucks says I can
beat you to the curb.

754
00:41:59,410 --> 00:42:00,850
Thanks for sticking with the case.

755
00:42:01,600 --> 00:42:02,660
I can't do anything else.

756
00:42:05,700 --> 00:42:07,620
You're much more easily
amused when you can walk.

757
00:42:07,970 --> 00:42:08,970
How bizarre.

758
00:42:10,220 --> 00:42:12,499
I'm guessing you
weren't exactly Mr. Sunshine

759
00:42:12,500 --> 00:42:14,500
even before your leg got messed up.

760
00:42:19,290 --> 00:42:20,390
I want you to have this.

761
00:42:31,180 --> 00:42:31,800
Wow.

762
00:42:32,200 --> 00:42:35,370
You can sell it if you want to,
